00:08:32.860 --> 00:08:36.270
Now, I'll explain in greater
detail what I think he meant

00:08:36.270 --> 00:08:37.920
by that later in my talk.

00:08:37.920 --> 00:08:40.900
But for the moment, I want
to also declare that Rhapsody

00:08:40.900 --> 00:08:43.430
in Blue is not a composition.

00:08:43.430 --> 00:08:47.130
It is an arrangement, and
as I hope to convince you,

00:08:47.130 --> 00:08:49.580
it has been an arrangement
from it's origins

00:08:49.580 --> 00:08:53.250
and it remains an arrangement
in the present day.

00:08:53.250 --> 00:08:55.680
The version of Rhapsody in Blue
that you were listening to prior

00:08:55.680 --> 00:08:58.430
to the start of my talk which
featured Leonard Bernstein

00:08:58.430 --> 00:09:01.530 position:56%
as pianist -- he was also
conducting the New York Philharmonic

00:09:01.530 --> 00:09:04.640
from the piano -- this
is also an arrangement.

00:09:04.640 --> 00:09:06.970
Well, technically it's an
arrangement of an arrangement.

00:09:06.970 --> 00:09:10.120
But I'll explain that to you
a little bit later in my talk.

00:09:10.120 --> 00:09:12.510
The point I want to make
clear here at the outside is

00:09:12.510 --> 00:09:16.500
that I consider arrangement
to be a form of composition.

00:09:16.500 --> 00:09:20.710
As such, the compositional history
of Rhapsody in Blue emerges only

00:09:20.710 --> 00:09:23.810
over the course of time and
through the contributions

00:09:23.810 --> 00:09:25.970
of a multitude of musicians.

00:09:25.970 --> 00:09:28.480
Specifically, arrangers.

00:09:28.480 --> 00:09:30.220
And it's through this
process of arrangement

00:09:30.220 --> 00:09:34.530 position:56%
that the Rhapsody has secured it's
iconic standing in American culture.

00:09:34.530 --> 00:09:36.270
Without arrangers including first

00:09:36.270 --> 00:09:39.650
and foremost a man named Ferde
Grofe, without arrangers,

00:09:39.650 --> 00:09:44.250 position:56%
whose to say that we would have ever
even heard about Rhapsody in Blue?

00:09:44.250 --> 00:09:47.200
Now, if that question is a bit
dubious to you, don't worry.

00:09:47.200 --> 00:09:48.500
You're in good company.

00:09:48.500 --> 00:09:51.950
George Gershwin himself would
have been doubtful as well.

00:09:54.200 --> 00:09:57.320 position:56%
So in the board room of the American
Society of Authors, Composers

00:09:57.320 --> 00:10:00.640
and Publishers which is more
commonly referred to as ASCAP,

00:10:00.640 --> 00:10:03.790
hang framed letters from
it's notable members.

00:10:03.790 --> 00:10:06.900
One of these letters from George
Gershwin to J. C. Rosenthall,

00:10:06.900 --> 00:10:10.670
the general manager of ASCAP
is where my story begins.

00:10:10.670 --> 00:10:18.030
In August of 1928, George
Gershwin wrote, "Mr. Jerome Kern

00:10:18.030 --> 00:10:20.210
at lunch the other day
brought to my attention

00:10:20.210 --> 00:10:23.200
that Ferde Grofe had listed among
his compositions The Rhapsody

00:10:23.200 --> 00:10:24.570
in Blue.

00:10:24.570 --> 00:10:27.880 position:56%
Mr. Kern said he objected to this at
the last meeting and he advised me

00:10:27.880 --> 00:10:29.810
to write to you about it.

00:10:29.810 --> 00:10:32.260
Mr. Grofe made a very
fine orchestration

00:10:32.260 --> 00:10:33.990
from my completed sketch

00:10:33.990 --> 00:10:37.350
but certainly had no
hand in the composing."

00:10:37.350 --> 00:10:40.000
And just above the
salutation, he adds,

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:42.300
"Hoping you will straighten
this out."

00:10:43.340 --> 00:10:46.190
Now, over the course of the
last 80 years, various critics

00:10:46.190 --> 00:10:49.210
and scholars have attempted
to straighten out the extent

00:10:49.210 --> 00:10:51.930
of Grofe's contributions
to the piece.

00:10:51.930 --> 00:10:54.580
We know that Gershwin did not
orchestrate Rhapsody in Blue due

00:10:54.580 --> 00:10:57.730
to time constraints,
inexperience, convention

00:10:57.730 --> 00:10:59.600
or some combination thereof.

00:10:59.600 --> 00:11:03.590
Rather, the task felled to Ferde
Grofe who was the primary arranger

00:11:03.590 --> 00:11:05.680
for the Paul Whiteman Orchestra.

00:11:05.680 --> 00:11:07.530
And the Paul Whiteman Orchestra,
of course, is the ensemble

00:11:07.530 --> 00:11:11.970
that premiered Rhapsody in
Blue on February 12, 1924.

00:11:11.970 --> 00:11:16.840
Whiteman's ensemble was neither a
typical symphonic orchestra nor a

00:11:16.840 --> 00:11:18.460
standard jazz band.

00:11:18.460 --> 00:11:20.650
Each of the three reed
players, for example,

00:11:20.650 --> 00:11:23.250
doubled on a multitude
of instruments.

00:11:23.250 --> 00:11:26.660
Ross Gorman who performed the
infamous opening clarinet glissando

00:11:26.660 --> 00:11:30.410
and swoop also played
obo, base clarinet,

00:11:30.410 --> 00:11:34.330
alto saxophone and
sopranino saxophone.

00:11:34.330 --> 00:11:37.560
The other two reed players
rotated between baritone, tenor,

00:11:37.560 --> 00:11:40.040
alto and soprano saxiphones.

00:11:40.040 --> 00:11:43.710 position:56%
Additionally, Whiteman's ensemble
featured two trumpets and trombones,

00:11:43.710 --> 00:11:46.550
a tuba player that also
played the string bass.

00:11:46.550 --> 00:11:48.590
There was a pianist,
a celeste player,

00:11:48.590 --> 00:11:51.600
a banjo player and a percussionist.

00:11:51.600 --> 00:11:53.280
For the premiere of
Rhapsody in Blue,

00:11:53.280 --> 00:11:56.360
the ensemble also added four
additional violins as well

00:11:56.360 --> 00:11:58.850
as two French horns and the
photo that you're seeing here

00:11:58.850 --> 00:12:01.090
on the screen was taken
just prior to the premere

00:12:01.090 --> 00:12:04.830
of Rhapsody in Blue in 1924.

00:12:04.830 --> 00:12:06.720
Now given the complexity
of the Whiteman Orchestra,

00:12:06.720 --> 00:12:08.150
it should not be surprising

00:12:08.150 --> 00:12:10.430
that Gershwin did not
orchestrate the original version

00:12:10.430 --> 00:12:12.080
of Rhapsody in Blue.

00:12:12.080 --> 00:12:14.740
So when the American public
first experienced the Rhapsody,

00:12:14.740 --> 00:12:17.690
it was through Ferde
Grofe's arrangement.

00:12:17.690 --> 00:12:20.100
Although the role of Grofe in
the initial creative process

00:12:20.100 --> 00:12:22.180
of the Rhapsody has
never been denied,

00:12:22.180 --> 00:12:25.420
the extent of his contributions
to the origins and ongoing life

00:12:25.420 --> 00:12:30.360
of the piece have been sidelined
due to his status as an arranger.

00:12:31.470 --> 00:12:34.580
Grofe began arranging Gershwin's
so-called completed sketch

00:12:34.580 --> 00:12:37.450
from a performance by the Whiteman
Orchestra before Gershwin had even

00:12:37.450 --> 00:12:39.260
finished composing it.

00:12:39.260 --> 00:12:42.030
As often repeated in historical
literature on the piece,

00:12:42.030 --> 00:12:45.210
Grofe apparently traveled
daily to Gershwin's apartment

00:12:45.210 --> 00:12:47.900
on West 110th Street in
New York City to pick

00:12:47.900 --> 00:12:51.180
up newly composed pages
of the Rhapsody.

00:12:51.180 --> 00:12:53.780
The original jazz band version
of Rhapsody in Blue came together

00:12:53.780 --> 00:12:58.000
in this way page by page leading
up to it's much celebrated debut

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:01.520
at Paul Whiteman's
experiment in modern music.

00:13:02.710 --> 00:13:07.370
The completed sketch to which
Gershwin refers in his letter

00:13:07.370 --> 00:13:13.240
to ASCAP survives as a 56 page
two piano short score manuscript

00:13:13.240 --> 00:13:14.540
in pencil.

00:13:14.540 --> 00:13:16.220
And that's seen here on the screen.

00:13:16.220 --> 00:13:18.670
As with all the manuscripts
incorporated into my talk tonight,

00:13:18.670 --> 00:13:21.330
it is housed within the Music
Division's holdings here

00:13:21.330 --> 00:13:23.610
at the Library of Congress.

00:13:23.610 --> 00:13:27.830
This completed sketch contains 26
specific instrumental assignments

00:13:27.830 --> 00:13:30.370
in a variety of hand and writing
implements that have resulted

00:13:30.370 --> 00:13:34.550
in divided assessments on
Grofe's overall contributions

00:13:34.550 --> 00:13:36.250
to the Rhapsody.

00:13:36.250 --> 00:13:40.030
Some scholars such as Howard
Pollack concluded that Grofe

00:13:40.030 --> 00:13:43.790
"scrupulously honored
Gershwin's intentions."

00:13:43.790 --> 00:13:45.660
Others such as Jerome Schwartz

00:13:45.660 --> 00:13:49.380
and Don Reno assigned
greater agency to Grofe.

00:13:49.380 --> 00:13:52.420
However, scholars on both
sides of the divide arrived

00:13:52.420 --> 00:13:55.750
at their conclusions under the
assumption that Grofe indeed worked

00:13:55.750 --> 00:13:57.340
from this pencil document.

00:13:57.340 --> 00:13:59.360
And I believe that he did not.

00:13:59.360 --> 00:14:03.710
Rather, it appears that Grofe
worked from a fair copy manuscript,

00:14:03.710 --> 00:14:07.370
a crucial third source document
that's previously unconsidered

00:14:07.370 --> 00:14:09.650
in literature on Rhapsody in Blue.

00:14:09.650 --> 00:14:16.410
