occurs at this very moment

00:28:29.710 --> 00:28:33.500
where Gershwin took a break from
completing the stride theme.

00:28:33.500 --> 00:28:35.950
Up to this point throughout
the first eight measures

00:28:35.950 --> 00:28:40.660
or so of the theme, it resembles
a standard what we call an AABA

00:28:40.660 --> 00:28:41.960
[inaudible] song form.

00:28:41.960 --> 00:28:44.560
That is, we have the
first four measures

00:28:44.560 --> 00:28:47.490
and then the next four measures
are repeated so it's kind

00:28:47.490 --> 00:28:50.570
of the same thing, A
then A and then this is

00:28:50.570 --> 00:28:53.130
where he takes the break right
at the end of that red box there.

00:28:53.130 --> 00:28:57.160
He begins sort of what
becomes the B theme.

00:28:59.010 --> 00:29:01.500
Now, instead of repeating
the A theme after the B theme

00:29:01.500 --> 00:29:05.090
as we would expect
in an AABA song form,

00:29:05.090 --> 00:29:07.910
Gershwin takes a little
bit of a detour.

00:29:07.910 --> 00:29:10.220
The rhythmic post and block
chord melody that's heard

00:29:10.220 --> 00:29:14.830
in this A theme evaporates into
a thrice repeating linking theme.

00:29:14.830 --> 00:29:16.130
See that here.

00:29:16.130 --> 00:29:18.150
One, two and three.

00:29:18.150 --> 00:29:22.580
And then this is punctuated by
four chords and a simple crash.

00:29:22.580 --> 00:29:23.880
I'm going to play this
for you in a minute

00:29:23.880 --> 00:29:25.580
so you can hear what
I'm talking about.

00:29:25.580 --> 00:29:27.740 position:56%
But the most important point here is

00:29:27.740 --> 00:29:31.430 position:56%
that these compositional choices
result in an ellision, an avoidance,

00:29:31.430 --> 00:29:35.590
of standard [inaudible] song form
and they move the piece forward

00:29:35.590 --> 00:29:38.450
with a rhapsodic finesse
so to speak.

00:29:38.450 --> 00:29:40.510
So here's what this
passage sounds like.

00:29:40.510 --> 00:29:51.090
[ Music ]

00:29:51.090 --> 00:29:52.890
Here's the B section.

00:29:52.890 --> 00:30:16.120
[ Music ]

00:30:16.120 --> 00:30:17.890
And then a cymbal crash there is

00:30:17.890 --> 00:30:20.700
where you would take the
78 rpm record and flip it

00:30:20.700 --> 00:30:24.180
over for the second
half of the recording.

00:30:25.760 --> 00:30:29.310
Now, a small yet revealing
moment in this portion

00:30:29.310 --> 00:30:32.750
of the third gathering provides an
important piece of written evidence

00:30:32.750 --> 00:30:34.620
in support of my argument
that Grofe depended

00:30:34.620 --> 00:30:37.530
on the ink score rather
then the pencil score.

00:30:37.530 --> 00:30:39.440
In the midst of transferring
music from the pencil

00:30:39.440 --> 00:30:42.360
to the ink manuscript for this
portion of Rhapsody in Blue,

00:30:42.360 --> 00:30:45.180
Gershwin introduced
various revisions.

00:30:45.180 --> 00:30:47.200
Other copyists involved
in the preparation

00:30:47.200 --> 00:30:50.260
of the ink score did
not revise such.

00:30:50.260 --> 00:30:51.950
So consider for example
a modification

00:30:51.950 --> 00:30:54.520
that occurs at measure 145.

00:30:54.520 --> 00:30:58.020
This measure links
the A and B sections

00:30:58.020 --> 00:31:02.470
of the so-called shuffle theme and
in pencil manuscript you see here,

00:31:02.470 --> 00:31:05.970
the transition consists only
of a D7, a dominant 7 D chord

00:31:05.970 --> 00:31:09.760 position:56%
and the treble cleft on the first
beat, and it's followed by this kind

00:31:09.760 --> 00:31:14.160
of ascending eighth note
scale on the base cleft.

00:31:14.160 --> 00:31:15.920
If you look at the ink manuscript,

00:31:15.920 --> 00:31:19.700
you can see that Gershwin added
three ascending eighth note diads

00:31:19.700 --> 00:31:23.490
to the treble cleft.

00:31:23.490 --> 00:31:26.720
These notes subsequently become
a brief trumpet [inaudible]

00:31:26.720 --> 00:31:29.590
in the Grofe Whiteman score.

00:31:29.590 --> 00:31:32.250
Had Grofe been working from the
pencil manuscript rather then the

00:31:32.250 --> 00:31:34.590
fair copy ink manuscript
at this point,

00:31:34.590 --> 00:31:37.170
no such [inaudible] would have
appeared in his final score

00:31:37.170 --> 00:31:39.470
for the Whiteman Orchestra.

00:31:40.590 --> 00:31:43.960
Additionally, Grofe mentions in
an interview from the early 1960's

00:31:43.960 --> 00:31:47.060
that such a fair copy
manuscript was in use.

00:31:47.060 --> 00:31:49.600
Grofe stated that at some point
in the process the preparation

00:31:49.600 --> 00:31:53.230
of his fair copy manuscript
became impractical because

00:31:53.230 --> 00:31:56.040
"time was getting short."

00:31:56.040 --> 00:31:58.120
I'd like to pause over
Grofe's observation

00:31:58.120 --> 00:32:01.570
that time was getting short and
return to my proposal that Rhapsody

00:32:01.570 --> 00:32:06.000
in Blue was composed even more
rapidly then previously considered.

00:32:06.000 --> 00:32:08.590
Although we cannot conclusively
align particular passages

00:32:08.590 --> 00:32:11.770
or groupings with specific dates,
a comparison between the pencil,

00:32:11.770 --> 00:32:15.110
ink in Grofe Whiteman scores
makes clear that Gershwin

00:32:15.110 --> 00:32:18.870
and as a result Grofe encountered
a lot of starts and stops

00:32:18.870 --> 00:32:22.510
in the process of setting
Rhapsody in Blue down on paper.

00:32:22.510 --> 00:32:25.270
I've already suggested that after
Gershwin began notating Rhapsody

00:32:25.270 --> 00:32:29.600
in Blue on January 7 that he got
as far as page 3 before attending

00:32:29.600 --> 00:32:31.970
to the premiere of
Sweet Little Devil.

00:32:31.970 --> 00:32:36.100
Assuming a return to work after
his Broadway premiere on the night

00:32:36.100 --> 00:32:40.230
of January 21, Gershwin would
have had only seven days

00:32:40.230 --> 00:32:43.750
to work before traveling to Boston
for a recital with Eva Gauthier

00:32:43.750 --> 00:32:46.420
on the evening of Tuesday,
January 29.

00:32:46.420 --> 00:32:49.390
Now, it's possible that Gershwin's
impending departure prompted the

00:32:49.390 --> 00:32:51.380
appearance of his hand
in that ink manuscript

00:32:51.380 --> 00:32:52.730
in that section that
I just showed you.

00:32:52.730 --> 00:32:55.440
And this also might coincide
with Grofe's subsequent demand

00:32:55.440 --> 00:32:59.460
that he stop waisting time
with a fair copy manuscript.

00:32:59.460 --> 00:33:01.920
Irregardless of what point
on the timeline Grofe began

00:33:01.920 --> 00:33:05.060
to use the pencil manuscript
instead of the ink manuscript,

00:33:05.060 --> 00:33:07.710
they were both clearly feeling
pressure to compose the Rhapsody

00:33:07.710 --> 00:33:10.170
in Blue and complete it
before it's premiere.

00:33:10.170 --> 00:33:12.920
The third and final public
rehearsal for Whiteman's experiment

00:33:12.920 --> 00:33:16.910
in modern music took place on
February 5, exactly one week

00:33:16.910 --> 00:33:19.470
after Gershwin's recital in Boston.

00:33:19.470 --> 00:33:22.600
So by my estimation, Rhapsody
in Blue was created in less

00:33:22.600 --> 00:33:26.950
than 14 days, about half as
long as we previously assumed.

00:33:26.950 --> 00:33:31.410
If Grofe's recollection is correct,

00:33:31.410 --> 00:33:33.900
then copying out the ink
score became impractical.

00:33:33.900 --> 00:33:36.390
It would explain the sudden
end of Gershwin's notation

00:33:36.390 --> 00:33:38.390
in the ink score of measure 174.

00:33:38.390 --> 00:33:40.190
The blue box here on
the screen shows you

00:33:40.190 --> 00:33:44.530 position:56%
where the new copyist takes over and
Gershwin's hand leaves the document.

00:33:44.530 --> 00:33:48.510
It seems that whenever Gershwin was
feeling particularly short on time

00:33:48.510 --> 00:33:51.390
that he inserted a piano
solo or a piano cadenza.

00:33:51.390 --> 00:33:53.550
We see this every single time
there's a break in the groupings

00:33:53.550 --> 00:33:55.920
or a break in the compositional
process

00:33:55.920 --> 00:33:58.320
where he gets stuck,
he starts a piano solo.

00:33:58.320 --> 00:33:59.620
So the next time you
listen to Rhapsody in Blue

00:33:59.620 --> 00:34:01.670
and you hear a piano cadenza
begin, you can think, "Oh,

00:34:01.670 --> 00:34:02.990
I know why Gershwin did that.

00:34:02.990 --> 00:34:04.290
He was pressed for time."

00:34:04.290 --> 00:34:09.460 position:56%
Now, this cadenza marks the onset of
142 consecutive bars of piano solo

00:34:09.460 --> 00:34:12.970
with little instrumental
accompaniment for Grofe to score.

00:34:12.970 --> 00:34:15.220
Clearly, it became more
practical for Grofe just to work

00:34:15.220 --> 00:34:18.860
from the pencil manuscript as the
premiere date drew ever closer.

00:34:18.860 --> 00:34:23.410
So contrary to previous assumptions
for at least the first 175 measures

00:34:23.410 --> 00:34:25.150 position:56%
of Rhapsody in Blue, Gershwin worked

00:34:25.150 --> 00:34:27.920
from the ink score rather
then the pencil manuscript.

00:34:27.920 --> 00:34:31.730 position:56%
Given that only 13 instrumental
indications appear in these measures

00:34:31.730 --> 00:34:34.690
and that Grofe chose
to ignore half of them,

00:34:34.690 --> 00:34:37.590
manuscript evidence suggests that
he was responsible for a majority

00:34:37.590 --> 00:34:41.690
of the scoring choices made in
the first third of his piece.

00:34:41.690 --> 00:34:45.280
This level of independence
persists even after measure 175,

00:34:45.280 --> 00:34:48.660
the point at which Grofe
began to use the pencil score.

00:34:48.660 --> 00:34:51.100
With the exception of a
single solo horn line,

00:34:51.100 --> 00:34:53.160
Gershwin provided no
further indication

00:34:53.160 --> 00:34:56.370
of instruments from
this point forward.

00:34:56.370 --> 00:34:58.060
So, why does all this matter?

00:34:58.060 --> 00:35:02.810
If Grofe indeed scored the Rhapsody
with a significantly greater degree

00:35:02.810 --> 00:35:05.040
of independence then
previously assumed,

00:35:05.040 --> 00:35:08.990
we can more directly address how a
selection of specific instruments

00:35:08.990 --> 00:35:12.370
and the implementation of other
jazz band arranging techniques

00:35:12.370 --> 00:35:15.340
transformed Gershwin's
so-called completed sketch

00:35:15.340 --> 00:35:19.590
into a fully fledged
musically engaging composition.

00:35:19.590 --> 00:35:21.480
In his landmark study
on Fletcher Henderson,

00:35:21.480 --> 00:35:25.810
musicologist Jeffrey McGee
states that "like a composer,

00:35:25.810 --> 00:35:30.300
an arranger gives original shape
to a piece of music creating unity

00:35:30.300 --> 00:35:33.940
and contrast through a
variety of musical elements

00:35:33.940 --> 00:35:36.350
like an improvising
soloist," McGee continues,

00:35:36.350 --> 00:35:40.070 position:56%
"an arranger takes existing material
and uses it as the framework

00:35:40.070 --> 00:35:42.940
for a fresh new inception."

00:35:44.440 --> 00:35:46.250
One reality of the
Rhapsody and indeed one

00:35:46.250 --> 00:35:47.970
of his most frequent criticisms is

00:35:47.970 --> 00:35:49.790
that large passages
offer little more

00:35:49.790 --> 00:35:53.200
than AABA [inaudible] style tunes.

00:35:53.200 --> 00:35:55.510
The decisions that Grofe made
in transitioning the Rhapsody

00:35:55.510 --> 00:35:57.570
from Gershwin's two
piano pencil score

00:35:57.570 --> 00:36:00.460
to the Whiteman arrangement
lends a piece and necessary level

00:36:00.460 --> 00:36:05.910
of coherence and unit for
tectural and tamboral variety.

00:36:05.910 --> 00:36:09.640
Thinking back to Gershwin's letter
to the general manager of ASCAP,

00:36:09.640 --> 00:36:14.520
can we define Grofe's role
as akin to that of Gershwin?

00:36:14.520 --> 00:36:16.690
Gershwin's first biographer,
Isaac Goldberg suggested

00:36:16.690 --> 00:36:17.990
that he might, that we might.

00:36:17.990 --> 00:36:21.010
He said, "The contribution of
Grofe was of prime importance.

00:36:21.010 --> 00:36:23.820
It is strange indeed that
he was not represented

00:36:23.820 --> 00:36:26.940
on Whiteman's program
as a composer."

00:36:26.940 --> 00:36:29.890
Gershwin, of course, strongly
disagreed with such a notion.

00:36:29.890 --> 00:36:31.850
Gershwin stated that, "The ability

00:36:31.850 --> 00:36:34.220
to orchestrate is a
talent completely apart

00:36:34.220 --> 00:36:36.410
from the ability to create.

00:36:36.410 --> 00:36:39.290
The world is full of the most
competent orchestrators who cannot

00:36:39.290 --> 00:36:42.620
for the life of them write
four bars of original music."

00:36:42.620 --> 00:36:48.060 position:56%
So for Gershwin then, it was the
themes rather then the overall sound

00:36:48.060 --> 00:36:52.180
of the rhapsody that
counted as the "composition."

00:36:52.180 --> 00:36:55.530
His perspective to conform to
his experience as a songwriter

00:36:55.530 --> 00:36:57.450
and as a man of the theater.

00:36:57.450 --> 00:36:58.750
In Gershwin's estimation,

00:36:58.750 --> 00:37:01.460
it was seen that orchestrators
offer little more than a paint

00:37:01.460 --> 00:37:05.280
by numbers approach, the
casual addition of color

00:37:05.280 --> 00:37:07.560
to a fully outlined work.

00:37:07.560 --> 00:37:11.530
However, as the ink manuscript
reveals, Grofe's contributions

00:37:11.530 --> 00:37:13.510
to the Rhapsody were
anything but casual,

00:37:13.510 --> 00:37:15.830
even given the time constraints
under which he worked.

00:37:15.830 --> 00:37:18.810
So this prompts an
important question.

00:37:18.810 --> 00:37:21.540 position:56%
If Grofe had been a lesser arranger,

00:37:21.540 --> 00:37:24.880
would the Rhapsody had become
the success that it did?

00:37:24.880 --> 00:37:27.670
After all, this is a work that
not only became legendary during

00:37:27.670 --> 00:37:30.130
Gershwin's lifetime
circulating as an arrangement

00:37:30.130 --> 00:37:34.020 position:56%
through life performance, recordings
and sheet music, but also as one

00:37:34.020 --> 00:37:36.960
that maintains a standing as one
of the quintessential examples

00:37:36.960 --> 00:37:38.680
of American concert music.

00:37:38.680 --> 00:37:42.240
Both the original Whiteman
arrangement and the arrangement

00:37:42.240 --> 00:37:45.480
for symphony orchestra that we are
perhaps more familiar with today,

00:37:45.480 --> 00:37:49.940
both of these arrangements
were prepared by Ferde Grofe.

00:37:49.940 --> 00:37:52.570
The decisions that Grofe made in
transitioning Rhapsody in Blue

00:37:52.570 --> 00:37:54.320
from Gershwin's two
piano pencil score

00:37:54.320 --> 00:37:58.500 position:56%
to the Whiteman arrangement lent the
piece necessary level of consistency

00:37:58.500 --> 00:38:00.970
through it's variety,
through it's novelty.

00:38:00.970 --> 00:38:04.730 position:56%
This variety and novelty is lost in
a subsequent arrangement of Rhapsody

00:38:04.730 --> 00:38:06.720
in Blue for the symphony orchestra.

00:38:06.720 --> 00:38:08.820
And some critics feel
that this arrangement,

00:38:08.820 --> 00:38:11.650
that it makes Rhapsody
suffer because of the result

00:38:11.650 --> 00:38:14.890 position:56%
