Rhapsody in Blue.

00:42:07.820 --> 00:42:12.920 position:56%
PM tells Bernstein that Gershwin
was "every inch a serious composer."

00:42:12.920 --> 00:42:15.550
But Bernstein cuts him off,
responding in a passage

00:42:15.550 --> 00:42:18.070
that has since become infamous.

00:42:18.070 --> 00:42:21.120
"Now PM, you know as well as I do

00:42:21.120 --> 00:42:23.970
that Rhapsody is not
a composition at all.

00:42:23.970 --> 00:42:26.770
It's a string of separate
paragraphs stuck together

00:42:26.770 --> 00:42:29.370
with a thin paste of
flour and water.

00:42:29.370 --> 00:42:33.590
Composing is a very different thing
from writing tunes after all."

00:42:34.780 --> 00:42:36.390
Gershwin aficionados
are quick to point

00:42:36.390 --> 00:42:39.090
out that Bernstein's subsequent
influence on the reception

00:42:39.090 --> 00:42:42.580 position:56%
of Rhapsody in Blue and of Gershwin,
biographer, Howard Pollack,

00:42:42.580 --> 00:42:45.440
suggests that a nice Gershwin
tune is solely the reputation

00:42:45.440 --> 00:42:49.060
of the work particularly since
it directly informed performance

00:42:49.060 --> 00:42:52.990
decisions made by Bernstein's
1959 recording.

00:42:52.990 --> 00:42:54.860
In spite of it's tremendous
popularity,

00:42:54.860 --> 00:42:57.350
David Schiff calls this
recording a "crisis

00:42:57.350 --> 00:43:00.390
in the performance
history of the piece."

00:43:00.390 --> 00:43:02.040
As musicologist, Larry
Starr observes,

00:43:02.040 --> 00:43:04.840
such considerations
typically "function as a kind

00:43:04.840 --> 00:43:08.260
of received wisdom or even
party line on Gershwin

00:43:08.260 --> 00:43:11.210
in academically critical circles."

00:43:11.210 --> 00:43:14.090
Upholding this doctrine, however,
assigns a degree of indifference

00:43:14.090 --> 00:43:16.930
to Bernstein where
one does not exist.

00:43:16.930 --> 00:43:19.910 position:56%
It also ignores the more complex
relationship that ultimately existed

00:43:19.910 --> 00:43:23.680
between Bernstein, Gershwin
and Rhapsody in Blue.

00:43:23.680 --> 00:43:27.830
Bernstein's essay did not simply
beget Bernstein's recording nor did

00:43:27.830 --> 00:43:31.070
either represent a hasty
interpretation of the Rhapsody.

00:43:31.070 --> 00:43:34.980 position:56%
They both resulted from his
multidecade relationship with piece,

00:43:34.980 --> 00:43:39.120
a relationship that emerges from
arrangements of Rhapsody in Blue.

00:43:39.120 --> 00:43:43.890
From an early age, Bernstein
had a fervent attraction

00:43:43.890 --> 00:43:45.550
to the music of George Gershwin.

00:43:45.550 --> 00:43:47.230
He purchased Gershwin's scores.

00:43:47.230 --> 00:43:49.430 position:56%
He staged his musicals with friends.

00:43:49.430 --> 00:43:53.150
He even attended the 1935
pre-Broadway tryout production

00:43:53.150 --> 00:43:57.690
of Porgy and Bess in Boston
when he was 17 years old.

00:43:57.690 --> 00:43:59.570
Throughout it all,
Rhapsody in Blue stands out.

00:43:59.570 --> 00:44:03.000
It's unclear when he first heard
the Rhapsody, but at the age

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:05.880
of 13 Bernstein begged
his father for money

00:44:05.880 --> 00:44:08.580
to buy a copy of the sheet music.

00:44:08.580 --> 00:44:10.770
Lifelong friend and colleague,
Syd Raymond [assumed spelling] was

00:44:10.770 --> 00:44:14.710
with the 13-year-old, Lennie, the
day that he purchased the $2 score.

00:44:14.710 --> 00:44:16.910
Syd Raymond who grew
up with Bernstein

00:44:16.910 --> 00:44:19.440
to become a successful Broadway
arranger on his own right,

00:44:19.440 --> 00:44:21.740
he worked with Bernstein
on Westside Story as well

00:44:21.740 --> 00:44:25.150
as several other Bernstein
works including The Mask.

00:44:25.150 --> 00:44:27.760
Recalling the day that his friend,
Lennie, purchased the sheet music

00:44:27.760 --> 00:44:30.260
for Rhapsody in Blue,
Raymond stated,

00:44:30.260 --> 00:44:33.480
"We went back to Lennie's
place, and he opened it.

00:44:33.480 --> 00:44:36.200
And at sight, he started
to play it because he was

00:44:36.200 --> 00:44:38.110
as you know a prodigious
sight reader.

00:44:38.110 --> 00:44:40.650
He could read almost
anything immediately."

00:44:40.650 --> 00:44:43.480
But he got to a certain
point, and he said, "You know,

00:44:43.480 --> 00:44:46.080
I wonder why Gershwin
wrote it in this key."

00:44:46.080 --> 00:44:50.300
And then Lennie started
to play it in another key.

00:44:50.300 --> 00:44:52.820
Bernstein purchased the solo piano
arrangement of Rhapsody in Blue

00:44:52.820 --> 00:44:57.100
that was first published by
Hermes of New York in 1927.

00:44:57.100 --> 00:45:00.750
Remarkably, Bernstein's own
copy of the sheet music survives

00:45:00.750 --> 00:45:02.990
in the New York Philharmonic
archives.

00:45:02.990 --> 00:45:10.100
The score shows signs of
frequent and animated use

00:45:10.100 --> 00:45:13.240
through it's Scotch tape binding
repairs and smudged corners

00:45:13.240 --> 00:45:15.100
from repeated page turning.

00:45:15.100 --> 00:45:18.170
There's a taunting remark about
Bernstein's sisters scrawled

00:45:18.170 --> 00:45:19.480
across the top of the front cover.

00:45:19.480 --> 00:45:24.070
It says, "Sure B has a
crush on Clarke Gable."

00:45:25.440 --> 00:45:28.340
Although such remarkings remind
us that this document is a product

00:45:28.340 --> 00:45:31.750
of adolescence, annotations
within the sheet music reveal

00:45:31.750 --> 00:45:33.050
that Bernstein's approach

00:45:33.050 --> 00:45:36.680
to the Rhapsody was really
anything but juvenile.

00:45:36.680 --> 00:45:39.180
Bernstein himself said of his first
experience with the sheet music.

00:45:39.180 --> 00:45:43.070
He said, "We went home and we
played it with tears until dawn.

00:45:43.070 --> 00:45:44.370
The excitement.

00:45:44.370 --> 00:45:47.430
We made our own sort of arrangement
so that we could do it forehand

00:45:47.430 --> 00:45:50.190 position:56%
and try to sound like an orchestra."

00:45:50.190 --> 00:45:53.470
So pencil markings found within
this manuscript record one

00:45:53.470 --> 00:45:55.060
such possible arrangement.

00:45:55.060 --> 00:45:59.980
There's 12 sets of brackets
that mark off the solo passages

00:45:59.980 --> 00:46:01.280
from the orchestral passages

00:46:01.280 --> 00:46:04.410
so that the two boys could have
traded the parts back and forth.

00:46:04.410 --> 00:46:08.170 position:56%
We also see in the score indications
such as [inaudible] where the piano

00:46:08.170 --> 00:46:10.040
and the orchestra would
have been played together

00:46:10.040 --> 00:46:13.430
in a forehand piano performance.

00:46:13.430 --> 00:46:16.640
Significantly, solo piano sheet
music that was acquired by the boys

00:46:16.640 --> 00:46:21.000
that fateful day contains a pair
of unique cuts that do not appear

00:46:21.000 --> 00:46:23.720
in previous or subsequent
publications of the sheet music.

00:46:23.720 --> 00:46:28.400
In fact, this 1927 score is
nearly 60 measures shorter

00:46:28.400 --> 00:46:30.760
than the more common two
piano arrangement of Rhapsody

00:46:30.760 --> 00:46:33.670 position:56%
in Blue published by Hermes in 1925.

00:46:33.670 --> 00:46:35.830
So when Leonard Bernstein first
learned to play the Rhapsody,

00:46:35.830 --> 00:46:39.240
it was with these cuts
firmy in place.

00:46:39.240 --> 00:46:43.160
So as a 13-year-old Bernstein
was already experimenting with

00:46:43.160 --> 00:46:45.970
and arranging Rhapsody in
Blue, and this personal copy

00:46:45.970 --> 00:46:50.210
of the sheet music documents many
of these musical explorations.

00:46:51.400 --> 00:46:55.600
Five years later, during the summer
of 1937, instead of spending time

00:46:55.600 --> 00:46:58.820
at the family's lakehouse
in Sharon, Massachusetts,

00:46:58.820 --> 00:47:01.980
the 18-year-old Bernstein
took a job at Camp Onota,

00:47:01.980 --> 00:47:06.100
a recently established all boys
Jewish camp in the Berkshires.

00:47:06.100 --> 00:47:10.010
Bernstein was in charge of a cabin
of campers from New York City,

00:47:10.010 --> 00:47:13.070
and he served as a
swimming counselor.

00:47:13.070 --> 00:47:16.380
Not surprisingly, he also
organized all musical activities,

00:47:16.380 --> 00:47:19.320
staging productions of Gilbert
and Sullivan's Parrots of Penzance

00:47:19.320 --> 00:47:21.640
and Gershwin's Of Thee I Sing.

00:47:21.640 --> 00:47:26.110
He formed small musical ensembles,
and he even wrote camp songs.

00:47:26.110 --> 00:47:31.800
The text of one surviving example
reads as follows, "Onota Camp,

00:47:31.800 --> 00:47:35.510
the end is near and soon we'll
have to say goodbye to you we fear.

00:47:35.510 --> 00:47:37.130
Our hearts are sad.

00:47:37.130 --> 00:47:42.270
Our eyes are damp because we have
to part with you, Onota Camp.

00:47:42.270 --> 00:47:44.150
Adon, adieu, and au revoir.

00:47:44.150 --> 00:47:46.360
Better time we never saw.

00:47:46.360 --> 00:47:48.680
We got the things that
we came here for.

00:47:48.680 --> 00:47:52.800
So adon, adieu, auf
wiederschen and au revoir."

00:47:54.730 --> 00:47:58.150 position:56%
Bernstein's lighthearted ditty takes
on a more poignant tune, however,

00:47:58.150 --> 00:47:59.450
when considered in the context

00:47:59.450 --> 00:48:04.280
of George Gershwin's sudden
death that very same summer.

00:48:04.280 --> 00:48:06.220
Gershwin died following
emergency surgery

00:48:06.220 --> 00:48:10.600
on an undiagnosed brain
tumor on July 11, 1937.

00:48:10.600 --> 00:48:11.900
The event had a profound

00:48:11.900 --> 00:48:14.260
and permanent effect
upon the young Bernstein.

00:48:14.260 --> 00:48:18.650
He later divulged, "The great
tragedy for me, the musical tragedy

00:48:18.650 --> 00:48:21.280 position:56%
of my life is that I never met him."

00:48:21.280 --> 00:48:25.630
And as a side note, today
actually marks the 25th anniversary

00:48:25.630 --> 00:48:30.580
of the passing of Leonard
Bernstein in 1990."

00:48:30.580 --> 00:48:33.060
In what appears to be a
tribute to his musical idol,

00:48:33.060 --> 00:48:36.550
Bernstein created his own
arrangement of Rhapsody in Blue,

00:48:36.550 --> 00:48:39.880 position:56%
which is located here in the
archives of the Library of Congress.

00:48:41.090 --> 00:48:43.490
This is the cover of the
Schomer's Harmony Tablet

00:48:43.490 --> 00:48:46.170
in which the arrangement
was located.

00:48:46.170 --> 00:48:50.060
And here are the first and
last pages of the manuscript.

00:48:51.790 --> 00:48:55.760 position:56%
Bernstein completed this arrangement
on August 10, 1937, almost one month

00:48:55.760 --> 00:48:58.330
to the day after Gershwin's death.

00:48:58.330 --> 00:49:00.870
The instrumentation of this
whimsical interpretation

00:49:00.870 --> 00:49:03.250
of the Rhapsody is notable.

00:49:03.250 --> 00:49:05.800
In addition to the
expected piano and clarinet,

00:49:05.800 --> 00:49:11.680
it calls for a recorder,
accordion, three male voices

00:49:11.680 --> 00:49:15.430
which also must whistle, two
ukuleles, and a percussion ensemble

00:49:15.430 --> 00:49:18.890
that he refers to as rhythm band.

00:49:18.890 --> 00:49:21.870
Bernstein's choices appear
to be largely delineated

00:49:21.870 --> 00:49:24.350
by the availability of
particular performers.

00:49:24.350 --> 00:49:26.770
If not performers then
at least instruments

00:49:26.770 --> 00:49:29.120
that we would find in
a camp environment.

00:49:29.120 --> 00:49:31.060
And while there's no record
that this arrangement was

00:49:31.060 --> 00:49:34.230
or was not performed, it does
appear to have been written

00:49:34.230 --> 00:49:38.620
with performers from
Camp Onota in mind.

00:49:38.620 --> 00:49:41.160
The clearest suggestion of this
appears in a photograph taken

00:49:41.160 --> 00:49:43.670
at camp that very same summer.

00:49:44.910 --> 00:49:48.700
This is the first known image
of Leonard Bernstein conducting.

00:49:48.700 --> 00:49:55.560
The caption reads, "Onota Rhythm
Band and Leonard Bernstein 1937."

00:49:55.560 --> 00:49:58.230
And this is the same
Rhythm Band called

00:49:58.230 --> 00:50:00.160
for in his Rhapsody arrangement.

00:50:00.160 --> 00:50:04.190
Dressed in his camp Onota tank
top, Bernstein directs a group

00:50:04.190 --> 00:50:06.480
of seven young musicians
who are playing a battery

00:50:06.480 --> 00:50:10.870
of percussion instruments including
two triangles, [inaudible], chimes,

00:50:10.870 --> 00:50:13.510
cymbals, a tamborine
and even what appears

00:50:13.510 --> 00:50:16.890
to be a kalimba or a thumb piano.

00:50:16.890 --> 00:50:19.220
Bernstein's camp arrangement
of the Rhapsody includes some

00:50:19.220 --> 00:50:20.740
of these very same instruments.

00:50:20.740 --> 00:50:22.210
So it's possible that
some of the boys seen

00:50:22.210 --> 00:50:26.660
in this photograph took part
in a performance of the piece.

00:50:26.660 --> 00:50:28.710
I had the pleasure of
editing a performing edition

00:50:28.710 --> 00:50:31.370
of this arrangement and with the
permission of both the Gershwin

00:50:31.370 --> 00:50:35.290
and Bernstein estates, the work had
it's world concert premiere during

00:50:35.290 --> 00:50:39.620
Harvard's Leonard Bernstein Boston
to Broadway festival back in 2006.

00:50:39.620 --> 00:50:42.480
It has not been heard
publicly since that time.

00:50:42.480 --> 00:50:45.620
So I'm particularly excited
to be able to share an excerpt

00:50:45.620 --> 00:50:49.090
from that performance
with you this evening.

00:50:49.090 --> 00:50:53.720
The clip that I'm going to play
begins at rehearsal letter J. It's

00:50:53.720 --> 00:50:56.030
on the second system
of this manuscript just

00:50:56.030 --> 00:51:02.080 position:56%
after the second piano cadenza which
is notated simply as piano cadenza.

00:51:02.080 --> 00:51:04.400
Earlier, I played contrasting
versions of the Rhapsody

00:51:04.400 --> 00:51:05.870
by Gershwin and Bernstein.

00:51:05.870 --> 00:51:09.440
This is the same solo piano
passage but here it's scored

00:51:09.440 --> 00:51:13.000
out for camp instruments and
should provide you with a sense

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:16.360
of the 18-year-old Leonard
Bernstein's overall approach

00:51:16.360 --> 00:51:24.510
to Rhapsody in Blue
in this arrangement.

00:51:24.510 --> 00:52:04.040
[ Music ]

00:52:04.040 --> 00:52:27.180
Feel free to sing along
if you'd like.

00:52:57.080 --> 00:53:00.210
We move into the piano cadenza,
which again is not notated

00:53:00.210 --> 00:53:03.050
because he would have
had it memorized.

00:53:03.050 --> 00:53:05.430
Now it's important to reiterate
that Bernstein's instrumentation

00:53:05.430 --> 00:53:08.670
in this passage replaces what would
have otherwise been an extended

00:53:08.670 --> 00:53:10.600
piano solo passage.

00:53:10.600 --> 00:53:13.420
That is, instead of just playing
these measures on the piano,

00:53:13.420 --> 00:53:16.400
he arranged them to be
played by his campers.

00:53:16.400 --> 00:53:20.180
The choices made here reflect
Bernstein's emerging theatricality.

00:53:20.180 --> 00:53:24.260 position:56%
The drama of the largo clarinet solo
sets up the playful reinterpration

00:53:24.260 --> 00:53:26.980
of the standard campfire
sing along, which is offered

00:53:26.980 --> 00:53:31.320
by disembodied textless
voices and ukuleles.

00:53:31.320 --> 00:53:34.530
In addition to the introduction
of imitative color combinations,

00:53:34.530 --> 00:53:36.890
we have this substitution
of the accordion

00:53:36.890 --> 00:53:41.740
for what would have otherwise been
rapid 16th note piano [inaudible].

00:53:42.830 --> 00:53:45.690
What this does is it
intensifies the dramatic arch

00:53:45.690 --> 00:53:49.470
of Gershwin's modulating melody to
which Bernstein adds a triumphant

00:53:49.470 --> 00:53:52.750
and newly composed clarinet solo.

00:53:52.750 --> 00:53:56.210
Such decisions foreshadow
the centrality of showmanship

00:53:56.210 --> 00:53:59.680
in Bernstein's future
presentations of Rhapsody in Blue.

00:53:59.680 --> 00:54:03.140
This excerpt from Camp Onota --

00:54:03.140 --> 00:54:06.800 position:56%
this excerpt from the Camp Onota
arrangement demonstrates Bernstein's

00:54:06.800 --> 00:54:11.160
continued compartmentalization
of Gershwin's themes.

00:54:11.160 --> 00:54:13.810
Much in the same way as the
annotative brackets function

00:54:13.810 --> 00:54:17.270
in Bernstein's 1927
solo piano sheet music,

00:54:17.270 --> 00:54:19.380
Bernstein here demarcates
transitions

00:54:19.380 --> 00:54:22.420
by [inaudible] grand
pauses, dramatic shifts

00:54:22.420 --> 00:54:24.400
in dynamic and instrumentation.

00:54:24.400 --> 00:54:28.830
And in one particularly striking
instance, he adds a transposition.

00:54:28.830 --> 00:54:32.560
This transposition occurs at
the entrance of the love theme.

00:54:35.240 --> 00:54:38.190
In Gershwin's original
Rhapsody, this theme is preceded

00:54:38.190 --> 00:54:40.310
by a B dominant seven
chord which sets

00:54:40.310 --> 00:54:42.490 position:56%
up a dominant [inaudible] five seven

00:54:42.490 --> 00:54:47.020
to one transition into
the key of E major.

00:54:47.020 --> 00:54:53.340
Now, when Bernstein resets it,
letter N in his manuscript,

00:54:53.340 --> 00:54:56.250
instead of moving to E major,
he transcribes the love theme

00:54:56.250 --> 00:54:59.410
up a third higher in
the key of G major.

00:54:59.410 --> 00:55:03.060
So let me play these [inaudible]
so you can hear the difference.

00:55:03.060 --> 00:55:05.100
[ Music ]

00:55:05.100 --> 00:55:07.510
This is the original.

00:55:07.510 --> 00:55:15.160
[ Music ]

00:55:15.160 --> 00:55:17.510
And this is Bernstein's.

00:55:17.510 --> 00:55:29.040
[ Music ]

00:55:29.040 --> 00:55:31.070
So why might Bernstein
have done this.

00:55:31.070 --> 00:55:33.080
You can hear, this
is very much in kind

00:55:33.080 --> 00:55:35.370
of a Broadway show
tunes style modulation,

00:55:35.370 --> 00:55:39.230
the kind that further heightens
the drama of the melody.

00:55:39.230 --> 00:55:41.320
But it also echoes Syd
Raymond's recollection

00:55:41.320 --> 00:55:43.960
about Bernstein's first
reading of the sheet music

00:55:43.960 --> 00:55:46.600
where Bernstein questioned why
Gershwin wrote it in one key

00:55:46.600 --> 00:55:48.710
and then proceeded to
play it in another key.

00:55:48.710 --> 00:55:53.520
I suspect that this transposition
here reflects that initial impulse.

00:55:55.180 --> 00:55:57.860
These earlier arrangements of the
piece, the solo piano sheet music

00:55:57.860 --> 00:55:59.420
and the Camp Onota arrangement,

00:55:59.420 --> 00:56:02.960
these effected Bernstein's mature
interpretations of the Rhapsody.

00:56:02.960 --> 00:56:04.970
As I mentioned, the
solo piano sheet music

00:56:04.970 --> 00:56:08.910
that Bernstein acquired
contains a number of unique cuts.

00:56:08.910 --> 00:56:12.340
According to an unpublished 1986
interview, this is the version

00:56:12.340 --> 00:56:13.640
that Bernstein preferred.

00:56:13.640 --> 00:56:16.700
He stated, "I have
to confess to you,

00:56:16.700 --> 00:56:19.870
and even if this is a public
confession, this is the way

00:56:19.870 --> 00:56:23.040
that I've always played it so that
when I do play it with orchestras,

00:56:23.040 --> 00:56:26.520 position:56%
and I've played it with many
orchestras, I have to redo the score

00:56:26.520 --> 00:56:28.060
to fit the way that I learned it

00:56:28.060 --> 00:56:30.260
because that is the
way that I love it.

00:56:30.260 --> 00:56:32.860
That is the way I know it,
and I think it works better."

00:56:32.860 --> 00:56:36.640
And in fact with the
exception of two measures,

00:56:36.640 --> 00:56:38.800
Bernstein's famous
recording of Rhapsody in Blue

00:56:38.800 --> 00:56:41.100
with the New York Philharmonic
follows the cuts taken

00:56:41.100 --> 00:56:44.810
in this 1927 solo piano
sheet music note for note.

00:56:44.810 --> 00:56:49.220
Now it's been said that the
cuts located in this recording

00:56:49.220 --> 00:56:53.510
"arguably undermine the
work's structural integrity."

00:56:53.510 --> 00:56:58.500 position:56%
However, if we return to Bernstein's
essay [inaudible] Gershwin tune,

00:56:58.500 --> 00:57:03.430
we see that Bernstein relished in
structural flexibility of the work.

00:57:03.430 --> 00:57:07.930
Bernstein states that with the
Rhapsody, "You can cut out parts

00:57:07.930 --> 00:57:12.110 position:56%
of it without affecting the whole in
any way except to make it shorter.

00:57:12.110 --> 00:57:14.060
You can remove any of these
stuck together sections

00:57:14.060 --> 00:57:16.860
and the piece still goes
on as bravely as before.

00:57:16.860 --> 00:57:18.540
You can even interchange
these sections

00:57:18.540 --> 00:57:21.130
with one another and
no harm is done.

00:57:21.130 --> 00:57:24.320
You can make cuts within a section
or add new cadenzas or play it

00:57:24.320 --> 00:57:27.860
with any combination of
instruments or on the piano alone.

00:57:27.860 --> 00:57:29.160
It can be a five minute piece

00:57:29.160 --> 00:57:32.100
or a six minute piece
or a 12 minute piece.

00:57:32.100 --> 00:57:36.810
And in fact, all of these things
are being done to it every day.

00:57:36.810 --> 00:57:39.130
It's still a Rhapsody in Blue."

00:57:39.130 --> 00:57:43.740
The considerations advanced
in this 1955 essay, however,

00:57:43.740 --> 00:57:45.310
were not recent validations.

00:57:45.310 --> 00:57:49.970
Considerations advanced in
this 1955 essay, however,

00:57:49.970 --> 00:57:52.780
were not recent revelations
to Bernstein.

00:57:52.780 --> 00:57:55.560
Rather, they were observations
formed while growing up,

00:57:55.560 --> 00:57:59.570
observations delineated in his camp
arrangement of Rhapsody in Blue.

00:57:59.570 --> 00:58:02.730
It makes various cuts,
connects separate sections

00:58:02.730 --> 00:58:04.680
and alters the orchestration.

00:58:04.680 --> 00:58:06.830
It even goes so far as
to change the key of one

00:58:06.830 --> 00:58:08.980
of the works most famous themes,

00:58:08.980 --> 00:58:13.100
something he discovered was a
possibility as early as 1931.

00:58:13.100 --> 00:58:15.820
As a recording of his camp
arrangement demonstrates,

00:58:15.820 --> 00:58:18.900
Bernstein's later remarks are true.

00:58:18.900 --> 00:58:21.320
Regardless of the alterations
made to the piece,

00:58:21.320 --> 00:58:24.060
it remains Rhapsody in Blue.

00:58:24.060 --> 00:58:31.020
So on paper, the composite record
made up by the copyright registry,

00:58:31.020 --> 00:58:33.480
published editions of the sheet
music and even the program

00:58:33.480 --> 00:58:36.960
for the work's premiere, on paper
George Gershwin remains the sole

00:58:36.960 --> 00:58:39.370
composer for Rhapsody in Blue.

00:58:39.370 --> 00:58:43.080
The piece will forever remain
George Gershwin's Rhapsody in Blue.

00:58:43.080 --> 00:58:46.690
But the creation and maintenance
of his iconicity results only

00:58:46.690 --> 00:58:49.070
from the arrangement
of the piece by a host

00:58:49.070 --> 00:58:52.060
of other musicians over
the course of time.

00:58:52.060 --> 00:58:55.560
In this sense, it's a work in
movement to borrow a phrase

00:58:55.560 --> 00:58:58.770
from [inaudible] and
philosopher, Umberto Eco.

00:58:58.770 --> 00:59:02.970
The Rhapsody remains an open
text for musical interpretation

00:59:02.970 --> 00:59:06.850
in large part because of
it's inherent flexibility.

00:59:06.850 --> 00:59:09.440
The notion that anyone can
make something of the piece

00:59:09.440 --> 00:59:12.910 position:56%
in whatever way they choose to do
so is what has made it so attractive

00:59:12.910 --> 00:59:16.670
to countless musicians over the
course of the past 90 years.

00:59:16.670 --> 00:59:19.320
Now my remarks this evening
have been limited to the roles

00:59:19.320 --> 00:59:22.860
of Ferde Grofe and Leonard
Bernstein, but a multitude

00:59:22.860 --> 00:59:25.840
of prominent and little known
musicians have also taken the

00:59:25.840 --> 00:59:28.800
Rhapsody on in their
own unique ways.

00:59:28.800 --> 00:59:32.320
In the jazz world, this includes
figures such as Duke Ellington,

00:59:32.320 --> 00:59:35.180
Ella Fitzgerald and Marcus Roberts.

00:59:35.180 --> 00:59:37.350
In the popular world, we see
arrangements by [inaudible],

00:59:37.350 --> 00:59:43.330
and Brian Wilson of the Beach Boys.

00:59:43.330 --> 00:59:44.950
We also encounter arrangements
of Rhapsody

00:59:44.950 --> 00:59:46.250
in Blue on the silver screen.

00:59:46.250 --> 00:59:50.670
You see it in Woody Allen's
Manhattan, Disney's Fantasia 2000

00:59:50.670 --> 00:59:53.440 position:56%
and Baz Luhrmann's The Great Gatspy.

00:59:53.440 --> 00:59:55.950
Let's also not forget
about United Airlines.

00:59:55.950 --> 01:00:02.330
Like a Rhapsody itself,
the story of Rhapsody

01:00:02.330 --> 01:00:04.760
in Blue unfolds continually.

01:00:04.760 --> 01:00:08.000
It moves from one musician,
venue or conception to the next

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:12.560 position:56%
without formal design or intent all
the while revealing new perspectives

01:00:12.560 --> 01:00:15.920
on that which has come before
and providing a platform

01:00:15.920 --> 01:00:19.400
for understanding future
encounters with the work.

01:00:19.400 --> 01:00:21.370
Arrangements of Rhapsody
in Blue tell the tale

01:00:21.370 --> 01:00:23.320
of it's owngoing composition.

01:00:23.320 --> 01:00:25.320
Both with respect to
the music itself

01:00:25.320 --> 01:00:28.480
and the history that surrounds it.

01:00:28.480 --> 01:00:29.850
The different collection
of arrangements

01:00:29.850 --> 01:00:33.520
and those considered here tonight
would result in different themes,

01:00:33.520 --> 01:00:36.470
raise different concerns and
provide alternate narratives

01:00:36.470 --> 01:00:38.800
about the past and the present.

01:00:38.800 --> 01:00:41.950
Nonetheless, the ultimate point
of approaching the Rhapsody

01:00:41.950 --> 01:00:45.100
through arrangements would
remain much the same.

01:00:45.100 --> 01:00:48.190
Shifting the emphasis away
from a centralized composer

01:00:48.190 --> 01:00:51.310
and text does not rescend
the iconic status

01:00:51.310 --> 01:00:54.230
of either George Gershwin
or Rhapsody in Blue.

01:00:54.230 --> 01:00:58.960 position:56%
Rather, it provides insight into
why their elevated standing persists

01:00:58.960 --> 01:01:01.540
in American culture today.

