01:09:51.470 --> 01:09:55.520
And there's just this -- I just
wanted to make this comment

01:09:55.520 --> 01:09:59.600
about Gershwin being
in Paris studying

01:09:59.600 --> 01:10:02.240 position:56%
with [inaudible] -- is that correct?

01:10:02.240 --> 01:10:05.240
And then bringing that training.

01:10:05.240 --> 01:10:08.580
She was a stickler for technique.

01:10:08.580 --> 01:10:15.850
Bringing that European classical
music training back and integrating

01:10:15.850 --> 01:10:22.590
that with jazz and creating this
whole style is just fascinating.

01:10:22.590 --> 01:10:28.780
And just this improvisatory
style of the jazz component.

01:10:28.780 --> 01:10:33.490
I think it makes me think
that perhaps composition

01:10:33.490 --> 01:10:39.880
as defined is more of a
classical music [inaudible]

01:10:39.880 --> 01:10:44.360
and arrangement is more in jazz.

01:10:44.360 --> 01:10:45.660
&gt;&gt; Ryan Raul Banagale: Right.

01:10:45.660 --> 01:10:48.860
and Gershwin certainly was working
within both of those, those mileus.

01:10:48.860 --> 01:10:52.500
And as far as Gershwin
goes with [inaudible],

01:10:52.500 --> 01:10:57.820 position:56%
it was more in a passing
relationship then an actual duration

01:10:57.820 --> 01:10:59.580
of study time.

01:10:59.580 --> 01:11:01.980
I think his encounter with
[inaudible] is similar

01:11:01.980 --> 01:11:06.800
to his encounter with [inaudible] I
think the story goes where he said,

01:11:06.800 --> 01:11:08.570
"I'd like to study with
you, Mr. [inaudible]."

01:11:08.570 --> 01:11:10.540
And [inaudible] apparently
said, "Well,

01:11:10.540 --> 01:11:13.260
how much money did
you make last year."

01:11:13.260 --> 01:11:16.500
Gershwin said, oh, something,
150,000 something like that.

01:11:16.500 --> 01:11:19.410
And he said, "Well then I should
be taking lessons from you."

01:11:19.410 --> 01:11:21.750
Well, that story is
probably [inaudible].

01:11:21.750 --> 01:11:24.520
It's also been assigned
to Stravinsky

01:11:24.520 --> 01:11:25.900
and I think also to Schoenberg.

01:11:25.900 --> 01:11:29.490
A lot of people apparently had this
same conversation with Gershwin.

01:11:29.490 --> 01:11:35.440
Nonetheless, he really did absorb
influences wherever he could

01:11:35.440 --> 01:11:36.740
find them.

01:11:36.740 --> 01:11:38.040
He certainly did spend
a lot of time in Paris.

01:11:38.040 --> 01:11:40.390
America and Paris is
probably the most famous --

01:11:40.390 --> 01:11:45.470
kind of compositional
result of that as well.

01:11:45.470 --> 01:11:48.040
The primary parts that he
studied was the composition

01:11:48.040 --> 01:11:51.140
after the Rhapsody in Blue
later on is Joseph Schillinger.

01:11:51.140 --> 01:11:55.710 position:56%
And really if you look at -- there's
been some wonderful studies on Porgy

01:11:55.710 --> 01:11:57.930
and Bess and the effect
of Schillinger and kind

01:11:57.930 --> 01:12:02.110
of the rotational compositional
aspects that Schillinger introduced

01:12:02.110 --> 01:12:05.900
to Gershwin that we can certainly
see in play in Porgy and Bess.

01:12:05.900 --> 01:12:10.730
1924, Gershwin still really
hadn't left the country

01:12:10.730 --> 01:12:12.760
with Rhapsody in Blue.

01:12:12.760 --> 01:12:15.080
This is not too long after
he'd had his first big hit

01:12:15.080 --> 01:12:16.380
with the [inaudible].

01:12:16.380 --> 01:12:19.870
1924 is the same year that
Lady Be Good was on stage

01:12:19.870 --> 01:12:21.330
and his first hit musical.

01:12:21.330 --> 01:12:24.450
Things really do take off in
1924, and he does start traveling

01:12:24.450 --> 01:12:25.810
around the world and meeting

01:12:25.810 --> 01:12:27.800
and having a lot of
different influences.

